Data Visualization using ggplot2 & plotly

Hao

6/17/2019

It is impossible to cover data visualization within one chapter. Here we are only trying to give you a basic demonstration of how to use ggplot2 & plotly to create figures easily in R. Again, this chapter is highly practical. We will show you how to design and make some common figures here but what you need is to learn by doing. Thanks to the rich community of ggplot2, you can always find a good support online if you ever run into problems in the future.

ggplot2

Grammar of Graphics Fundementals

Let’s start with a basic example of using ggplot2. This time, we are going to use the iris data set.

head(iris)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa
library(tidyverse)

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2)

ggplot understands graphics in a very artistic way:

Plot = A canvas + Different layers of visuals

When we are creating a ggplot, we always start with a ggplot function, which gives us a canvas. In fact, if you run the ggplot() function by its own, you will get a blank plot.

ggplot()

Layers of visuals in ggplot2 are called geom. The geom provides some pre-defined rules on how the points, lines or shapes should be drawn. For example, the geom_point() function we used previously contains instructions of how to draw a layer of points, which basically tells R that you want to use your data to draw a scatter plot. As far as today, there are 48 pre-defined geoms available in ggplot2 for you to choose. In most cases, these geom can cover most of what you need and satisfy most of your imagination. If you need more, there are plenty of ggplot2 extension packages online. Some of them do provide additional geoms. You can find a list of these extension package on this website: https://www.ggplot2-exts.org

Geoms in base ggplot2:

You can add multiple layers of geoms into the same plot. In the example below, we are adding a semi-transparent path line on top of the points layer. Note that, the path geom also uses the “data” and x-y definitions we defined in the ggplot() function.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4)

You can also get some hints on which geom to use by checking out the ggplot2 cheatsheet. You can find one here:

https://github.com/rstudio/cheatsheets/blob/master/data-visualization-2.1.pdf

It is also critically important to understand where to put “variables” here. Let’s take a look at example 1 again. There are 3 kinds of variables here:

  • data: The first variable in ggplot() or inside data = in any geoms.
  • variable aesthetics: Variables defined within aes()
  • constant aesthetics: variables defined outside aes()
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2)

The data and aes() defined in ggplot() globally affects the entire “canvas”. You can also define them locally within each geom. This is especially helpful if you want to add a layer of data, which was not included in the orginal dataset.

# The previous example can be rewritten as below.
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species), 
             shape = 2)

Scale

In previous examples, we have used the aes() function to assign data into several aesthetic aspects, such as the x & y axis. Common aesthetic variable include:

  • x
  • y
  • color/colour
  • fill
  • alpha
  • size
  • linetype
  • shape

The default settings in ggplot works in certain ways but we always want to be able to customize these settings. In fact, these aesthetic aspects can then be further customized using the family of scale function. Here we listed out all scale functions in base ggplot2:

You can simply “add” these scale functions into your ggplot calls.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_x_log10() + # log transformation for x axis
  scale_y_reverse() + # reverse y axis
  scale_color_viridis_d() # viridis color makes plots look scientific. 

                          # _d means discrete. _c means continuous.

Coorinate

Although scale can modify axes, these modifications belongs to the individual axis. If what you want to change is something beyond that, for example, the relationship/layout between the axes, you need to use the coord_ coordinate function family.

For example, coord_polar() will squeeze the axes and transform the plot into a radar plot whereas coord_fixed() will force the two axes to use the same scale to show their 1:1 (or customized) relationship. What I find most useful is the coord_flip() function, which can flip the x-y axis. This is really helpful when you make a forest plot.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  coord_polar()

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  coord_fixed()

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  coord_flip()

Facets

Facets in ggplots refers to multiple subpanels of the “same” plot. It can be done through the facet_grid() (2D) or face_wrap() (1D) functions.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  facet_wrap(~Species)

Theme

theme_ family

Theme in ggplot controls how the plot will look in general, such as the color of the panel and the font of the axis. ggplot2 comes with a few pre-defined themes. You can access them through the theme_ prefix. For example, theme_minimal will remove the gray background and borders from the default of ggplot2.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  theme_minimal()

Here at Markus Institute, we also spent some time and developed this razor theme.

library(ggrazor)

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point(shape = 2) + 
  geom_path(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_color_viridis_d() +
  theme_razor() +
  # you can add additional stuff to make it look better.
  theme(axis.line = element_blank()) +
  ggthemes::geom_rangeframe(data = data.frame(x = c(4, 8), y = c(2, 6)),
                            aes(x, y), color = "#7F7F7F", show.legend = F)

theme() function

If you are looking into customizing the theme in details, which we usually do, you need this theme function. Here is a reference page of what you can do but in most cases, you can find what you need via auto-complete in RStudio.

https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ggtheme.html

Position dodge/jitter

Most geoms come with a position argument. You can adjust the position of the points/bars a little so that they are not over lapping. However, dodge/jitter do not only help you get away with overlapping points, they can also help you make culstered plots.

iris_sum <- iris %>%
  gather("key", "value", -Species) %>%
  group_by(Species, key) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(value),
            sd = sd(value)) %>%
  mutate(low = mean - 1.96 * sd, high = mean + 1.96 * sd)
head(iris_sum)
## # A tibble: 6 x 6
## # Groups:   Species [2]
##   Species    key           mean    sd    low  high
##   <fct>      <chr>        <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 setosa     Petal.Length 1.46  0.174 1.12   1.80 
## 2 setosa     Petal.Width  0.246 0.105 0.0394 0.453
## 3 setosa     Sepal.Length 5.01  0.352 4.32   5.70 
## 4 setosa     Sepal.Width  3.43  0.379 2.69   4.17 
## 5 versicolor Petal.Length 4.26  0.470 3.34   5.18 
## 6 versicolor Petal.Width  1.33  0.198 0.938  1.71
ggplot(iris_sum, aes(x = Species, y = mean, ymin = low, ymax = high,
                     color = key)) +
  geom_pointrange(position = position_dodge(0.5)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = key), 
            position = position_dodge(0.5), vjust = 1.5) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  theme_minimal()
